<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900618-0044</DOCNO><DOCID>900618-0044.</DOCID><HL>   What's News --   Business and Finance</HL><DATE>06/18/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1</SO><LP>   DONALD TRUMP'S debt includes more than $500 million inbank loans that he personally guaranteed, bankers say.Lenders are increasingly seeking the liquidation of most ofhis properties, and demanding that he relinquish day-to-daycontrol of his operations. The market value of his assets isbelieved to fall well short of the amount the developer hasborrowed. Trump missed $73 million in debt payments that weredue Friday.   ---</LP><TEXT>   UAL's nonunion workers may oppose the proposed unionbuy-out of the company. Such a stance could pose apublic-relations problem for the takeover group as it seeksfinancing.   ---   The domination of big airports by one or two airlines isthe subject of a broad Justice Department investigation intopossible antitrust violations. Prosecutors have asked USAirfor information about the allocation of gates at a newterminal in Pittsburgh.   ---   An after-hours system for trading stocks and stock optionsis to be announced today by the American and Cincinnatiexchanges, the Chicago Board Options Exchange and Reuters.The alliance is a response to the Big Board's nighttimetrading plans.   ---   Norway's oil minister said the North Sea producer willprobably stop limiting its output, a practice begun fouryears ago in a gesture of good will to OPEC. The country'sposture could rattle jittery petroleum markets.   ---   Factory output rose 0.6% in May as auto productionrebounded. Consumer prices increased a modest 0.2% during thesame month. Economists say the figures depict continued slowgrowth with steady inflation.                                                                                                          The U.S. merchandise trade gap narrowed to $6.94 billionin April as a 6.2% plunge in imports more than offset a 3.5%decrease in exports.   ---   Bond prices fell sharply Friday on astronger-than-expected industrial-production report, whilestocks were mixed. Broad stock-market measures ended littlechanged, but the Dow Jones Industrial Average gained 7.67points to 2935.89, a new high.   ---   Ford raised base prices on many cars and trucks, its firstmidyear increases in three years. The move comes despitelagging auto sales. The boosts range from $58 to $134.   ---   Thrift-bailout officials transferred $2.1 billion indeposits from two insolvent Sandamp;Ls to Sunbelt Savings ofDallas. The action, intended to make government-owned Sunbeltmore attractive to potential buyers, will cost taxpayers anestimated $1.68 billion.   ---   Martin A. Siegel was sentenced to two months in prison forsecurities fraud. The judge cited the former Kidder Peabodytakeover strategist's cooperation in the federal government'sinsider-trading probe.   ---   Businessland dismissed the two executives in charge ofmarketing and sales, reflecting management's concern aboutthe computer retailer's performance in those areas.   ---   Hewlett-Packard today is to introduce its firstworkstations incorporating the product line of ApolloComputer, which the company acquired last year for $476.4million.   ---   Markets --   Stocks: Volume 205,130,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials2935.89, up 7.67; transportation 1193.25, off 2.19; utilities211.71, off 1.38.   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3432.58, off26.79.   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 130.56, up 0.07; spotindex 129.48, off 0.36.   Dollar: 153.90 yen, off 0.27; 1.6875 marks, off 0.0060.</TEXT></DOC>